#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:2
msgid "Compensating"
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:4
msgid ""
"C2_Can substitute an equivalent term for a word/sign they can’t recall, so "
"smoothly that it is scarcely noticeable."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:6
msgid ""
"C1_Can exploit their range of vocabulary options creatively so as to readily "
"and effectively use circumlocution in almost all situations."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:8
msgid ""
"B2+_Can use circumlocution and paraphrase to cover gaps in vocabulary and "
"structure."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:10
msgid ""
"B2_Can address most communication problems by using circumlocution, or by "
"avoiding difficult expressions."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:13
msgid ""
"B1+_Can define the features of something concrete for which they can’t "
"remember the word/sign."
"Can convey meaning by qualifying a word/sign meaning something similar (e.g. "
"a truck for people = bus)."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:16
msgid ""
"B1_Can use a simple word/sign meaning something similar to the concept they "
"want to convey and invite “correction”."
"Can “foreignise” word/signs in their first language and ask for confirmation."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:18
msgid ""
"A2+_Can use an inadequate word/sign from their repertoire and use gestures "
"to clarify what they mean."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:20
msgid ""
"A2_Can identify what they mean by pointing to it (e.g. “I’d like this, "
"please”)."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:22
msgid "A1_Can use gestures to support simple words/signs in expressing a need."
msgstr ""

#: strategies-compensating_en.txt:23
msgid "Pre-A1_Can point to something and ask what it is."
msgstr ""
